    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1984-01-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1984-01-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="313"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d313">
                <head>313. Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> to
                    Tunisian President <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d313fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Executive
                        Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Head of State File,
                        Tunisia: President <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>
                        (8302445–8408275). No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1984-01-09">January 9, 1984</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Mr. President:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have sent <persName corresp="#p_WVAD_1">Dick Walters</persName>, a trusted
                    aide, to speak with you about my concern over the recent unrest in Tunisia. I
                    applaud your courage in facing up to Tunisia’s economic challenge and I
                    understand how difficult it was to deal with the disorders. Tunisia’s friends
                    will now want to consider how they can help your government and we in the United
                    States are considering ways to do so.</p>
                <p>With regard to the external threat, I have requested General <persName
                        corresp="#p_WVAD_1">Walters</persName> to share with you our latest
                    assessment of Libyan activities in the region, and to reassure you of our
                    continuing efforts to monitor Libyan activities. The United States remains
                    concerned for the continued security and territorial integrity of Tunisia.</p>
                <p>I know you will speak candidly to <persName corresp="#p_WVAD_1">Dick
                        Walters</persName> and I look forward to a report from him upon his
                        return.<note n="2" xml:id="d313fn2">For a record of <persName
                            corresp="#p_WVAD_1">Walters</persName>’s visit, see <ref target="#d315"
                            >Document 315</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ronald Reagan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
